{{for|the OS virtualization/emulation technology|Branded zones}} <!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Brandz.gif|300px|thumb|right|The BrandZ logo.]] -->
'''BrandZ''' is a [[brand equity]] [[database]] managed by the marketing firm [[Millward Brown]]. It holds data from over 650,000 consumers and professionals across 31 countries, comparing over 23,000 [[brand]]s.<ref name=g>[http://www.theage.com.au/news/business/global-brand-values-in-the-hot-seat/2006/05/22/1148150186776.html?page=fullpage#contentSwap1 Global brand values in the hot seat], Mark Ritson, ''The Age'', May 23, 2006. Accessed on line November 30, 2007.</ref><ref name=b>[http://www.brandz.com/ BrandZ - brand equity] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213021754/http://www.brandz.com/ |date=February 13, 2008 }}. Accessed on line November 30, 2007.</ref> The database is used to estimate brand valuations, and each year since 2006, has been used to generate a list of the top 100 global brands.<ref name=g /><ref>[http://moreresults.factiva.com/results/index/index.aspx?ref=MKTW000020060421e24k0001t VIEWPOINT: Step nearer to brand valuation 'perfection'], ''Marketing Week'', April 20, 2006. Accessed on line November 30, 2007.</ref>
==Controversy== {{Undue weight section|date=August 2018}} The credibility of the [[Interbrand]] and BrandZ league tables have been cast into doubt by an article written in [[Marketing Week]] by Mark Ritson.<ref>http://www.marketingweek.co.uk/sectors/industry/brand-valuations-do-not-always-tell-the-full-story/3030524.article</ref> The lack of clear definitions and valuation dates in the both companies methodology raise questions about the subjectivity involved in brand valuations. Being part of multinational advertising groups, Interbrand and Kantar Millward Brown also suffer from the risk of objectivity. [[Transparency (behavior)|Transparency]] and objectivity are two of the requirements of the [[ISO 10668]] standard of monetary brand valuations.
