{{Infobox Software | name = Receiver | logo = | screenshot = Citrix Receiver.png | caption = | developer = [[Citrix]] | latest_release_version = | latest_preview_date = | operating_system = [[Windows NT]], [[macOS]], [[Linux]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[Windows Phone 8]] | genre = [[Desktop Virtualization]] | license = [[Freeware]], [[source-available]] }} '''Citrix Receiver''' is the [[client (computing)|client]] component of [[XenDesktop]] and [[XenApp]], developed by [[Citrix Systems]]. It was released initially in 2009.
==Product overview== Citrix Receiver is the client component of XenDesktop or XenApp.<ref name=Lardinois14>{{cite news |title=Google And Citrix Team Up To Launch A Better Citrix Receiver For Chrome OS|author=Frederic Lardinois|url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/08/21/google-and-citrix-team-up-to-make-chromebooks-more-attractive-to-businesses/ |work=techcrunch.com |date=21 August 2014 | accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref> Devices with Receiver installed are able to access full desktops via XenDesktop or individual applications via XenApp from a centralized host, such as a [[Server (computing)|server]] or [[Cloud computing|cloud infrastructure]].<ref name=Musthaler11>{{cite news |title=Citrix Receiver brings full-fledged desktop apps to smartphones and tablets |first=Linda |last=Musthaler |url=http://www.networkworld.com/article/2183702/infrastructure-management/citrix-receiver-brings-full-fledged-desktop-apps-to-smartphones-and-tablet.html |work=networkworld.com | date=2 December 2011 | accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref> The product's intended users are employees.<ref name=Weedmark>{{cite news |title=How Does the Citrix Receiver for the iPhone Work? |first=David |last=Weedmark|url=http://everydaylife.globalpost.com/citrix-receiver-iphone-work-33551.html|work=everydaylife.globalpost.com|date= | accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref>
Citrix Receiver is not a standalone product and is included with XenApp and XenDesktop.<ref name=Woods11>{{cite news |title=Citrix expands Receiver support to one billion devices |author=Ben Woods |url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/citrix-expands-receiver-support-to-one-billion-devices/ |work=[[ZDNet]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=May 27, 2011 |accessdate=1 October 2015}}</ref>
Reviews praised Citrix Receiver's reasonably fast loading time<ref name="Blackwell2010">{{cite web | last = Blackwell | first = Gerry | title = Review: Citrix Receiver for iPad | work = EnterpriseMobileToday | publisher = QuinStreet Inc | date = July 29, 2010 | url = http://www.enterprisemobiletoday.com/reviews/article.php/3895756/Review-Citrix-Receiver-for-iPad.htm | accessdate = 18 November 2015 }}</ref> and flexibility in allowing remote desktop access from many different computer and mobile platforms.<ref name="Battersby15">{{cite web | last = Battersby| first = Jeffery | title = Citrix Receiver for iPhone | work = [[Macworld]] | publisher = [[IDG]] | date = | url = http://www.macworld.com/article/1142363/citrixreceiver.html | accessdate = 18 November 2015 }}</ref> However, reviewers also criticized the iPhone version of the software for the difficulty of formatting text and prolonged typing, tasks that normally required a keyboard and mouse.<ref name="Battersby15"/> The iPad version had similar accessibility issues, and the performance of flash applications was very limited.<ref name="Blackwell2010"/> As a remedy, Citrix developed a mouse for iOS devices.<ref>{{cite web | last = Broida | first = Rick | title = Citrix to launch iOS-compatible mouse | work = [[CNET]] | publisher = [[CBS Interactive]] | date = May 7, 2015 | url = http://www.cnet.com/news/citrix-to-launch-first-ios-compatible-mouse/ | accessdate = 11 December 2015 }}</ref>
==History== Prior to Receiver, Citrix had a different client for each of its products. The company developed Receiver to handle the management of those clients.<ref name=Koetzing12>{{cite news |title=Understanding Citrix Receiver |first=Thomas |last=Koetzing |url=http://www.koetzing.eu/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=361&Itemid=310 |work=koetzing.eu | date=9 October 2012 | accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref> Citrix Receiver was announced in 2009 and the first version became available later that year.<ref name=Madden09>{{cite news |title=What's the difference between the "ICA client," the "XenApp Plug-in," and the "Citrix Receiver?" A guide to Citrix's client names and variants |first=Brian |last=Madden |url=http://www.brianmadden.com/blogs/brianmadden/archive/2009/05/19/what-s-the-difference-between-the-quot-ica-client-quot-the-quot-xenapp-plug-in-quot-and-the-quot-citrix-receiver-quot-a-guide-to-citrix-s-client-names-and-variants.aspx |work=brianmadden.com | date=19 May 2009 | accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref> Citrix Receiver won several mobility awards after its release, including a CRN Appy and "Best of [[Interop]]" award for Wireless & Mobility in 2011,<ref name=InformationWeek11>{{cite news |title=Interop's Best Of The Best, Network Concerns |url=http://www.networkcomputing.com/data-centers/interops-best-of-the-best-network-concerns/d/d-id/1232730? |work=[[InformationWeek]] | date=13 May 2011 | accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref> and a Global Mobile Award in 2012.<ref name=Acharya12>{{cite news |title=MWC 2012: Winners of Global Mobile Awards |first=Sarmistha |last=Acharya |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/winners-2012-global-mobile-awards-world-congress-308476 |work=[[International Business Times]] | date=3 March 2012 | accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref>
