{{Infobox video game | title = Sea Trader: Rise of Taipan | image = File:Sea Trader Rise of Taipan.jpg | alt = | caption = | developer = [[Jaleco Entertainment]] | publisher = [[Jaleco Entertainment]] | released = {{date|November 13, 2002|mdy}} | genre = Simulation game | modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]] | platforms = [[Game Boy Advance]] }}
'''''Sea Trader: Rise of Taipan''''' is a simulation [[video game]] developed and published by [[Jaleco Entertainment]]'s American division. The game was released exclusively in North America on November 13, 2002 for the [[Game Boy Advance]]. In ''Sea Trader'', the player controls a ship and tries to build a trading empire by selling goods between different ports. Reception was mixed, with praise directed towards the game's addictive nature while criticism focused on its dated graphics and its somewhat bare-bones gameplay.
==Gameplay== ''Sea Trader: Rise of Taipan'' is a shipping simulation game, where the player's goal is to make as much money as possible.<ref name="GS">{{cite web |title=Sea Trader: Rise of Taipan Review |author=Provo, Frank |date=January 29, 2003 |publisher=[[GameSpot]] |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/sea-trader-rise-of-taipan-review/1900-2909814/ |accessdate=July 3, 2018}}</ref><ref name="IGN">{{cite web |title=Sea Trader: Rise of Taipan |author=Harris, Craig |date=January 23, 2003 |publisher=[[IGN]] |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2003/01/23/sea-trader-rise-of-taipan |accessdate=July 3, 2018}}</ref> The player makes profit by buying goods in one port and then selling them in another.<ref name="IGN" /> Players can also use money to bribe [[Customs officer|customs officials]] into allowing them to offload illicit goods that are worth more money.<ref name="IGN" /> The game takes place over a one, five, or ten year period depending on the player's choice at the beginning of the game.<ref name="IGN" /> Money is used to upgrade the player's ship, bribe bartenders into getting gossip and tips, as well as buying maps to access more ports among other things.<ref name="IGN" /> Random encounters with pirates and other events happen during transit between ports—the action is always confined to menus, and contains little gameplay outside the economics simulation of the game.<ref name="GS" /><ref name="IGN" />
==Reception== The game received mixed reviews from critics, who felt that the game managed to be addictive despite its lackluster gameplay and graphics. It has received a 68% from review aggregator [[Metacritic]].<ref name="mc">{{cite web |title=Sea Trader: Rise of Taipan for Game Boy Advance reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/game-boy-advance/sea-trader-rise-of-taipan |accessdate=July 3, 2018}}</ref> [[IGN]]'s Craig Harris praised the game's replayability and addictive nature, but criticized its lack of "pizazz".<ref name="IGN" /> [[GameSpot]]'s Frank Provo called the game a "welcome change" and noted that it was a "relatively unique" experience for handheld systems like the Game Boy Advance.<ref name="GS" /> ''[[GamePro]]'' criticized the game for having "no action to speak of".<ref name="GamePro">{{cite web |title=Sea Trader: Rise of Taipan |publisher=[[GamePro]] |url=http://www.gamepro.com/nintendo%2Fgameboy_advance%2Fgames%2Freviews%2F27721.shtml |archive-date=September 5, 2003|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030905180341/www.gamepro.com/nintendo%2Fgameboy_advance%2Fgames%2Freviews%2F27721.shtml |deadurl=yes |accessdate=July 3, 2018}}</ref>
